{{Short description|Japanese clan of the Yamato period}}
{{Expand Japanese|大伴氏|date=December 2020}}
{{Infobox family
| name = Ōtomo
| native_name = 大伴氏
| native_name_lang = ja
| members = [[Ōtomo no Kanamura]]<br />[[Ōtomo no Tabito]]<br />[[Ōtomo no Yakamochi]]<br />[[Ōtomo no Sakanoue no Iratsume]]<br />[[Ōtomo no Otomaro]]<br />[[Tomo no Yoshio]]
}}
The {{nihongo|'''Ōtomo clan'''|大伴氏|Ōtomo uji}} was an aristocratic kin group [[Uji (clan)|(''uji'')]] of the {{ill|Yamato period|en|Yamato period|WD=Q633881|lt=Yamato period}}. The Ōtomo were known for their military strength and (along with other militarily valuable clans like the [[Heguri clan|Heguri]] and [[Mononobe clan|Mononobe]]) supplanted the formerly dominant [[Katsuragi clan]] as the most powerful clan at the {{ill|Yamato Kingship|en|Yamato Kingship|WD=Q2658252|lt=Yamato court}} during the fifth century.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Cambridge History of Japan, Volume 1: Ancient Japan |first=Delmer M. |last=Brown |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1993 |isbn=0521223520 |page=137}}</ref>

The Ōtomo clan lost imperial favor in 540 when {{ill|Emperor Kinmei|en|Emperor Kinmei|WD=Q329792|lt=Emperor Kinmei}} sided against the advice of [[Ōtomo no Kanamura]] that a military expedition be sent against the Korean kingdom of {{ill|Silla|en|Silla|WD=Q28456|lt=Silla}}, and stripped Kanamura of the title of [[Muraji|''ōmuraji'']]. The Ōtomo clan likely also lost Kinmei's favor because they had led the clans supporting the succession of [[Emperor Ankan]] and {{ill|Emperor Senka|en|Emperor Senka|WD=Q329728|lt=Emperor Senka}} to {{ill|Emperor Keitai|en|Emperor Keitai|WD=Q349277|lt=Emperor Keitai}}, while the clans supporting Kinmei's claim were led by the [[Soga clan]]. Soga clan leader {{ill|Soga no Iname|en|Soga no Iname|WD=Q595897|lt=Soga no Iname}} would become the most influential minister at Kinmei's court following Kanamura's removal in 540.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Cambridge History of Japan, Volume 1: Ancient Japan |first=Delmer M. |last=Brown |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=1993 |isbn=0521223520 |page=155}}</ref>

